    |<strong>In many regions, the depth of seasonally {Glossary.*Frozen_ground frozen ground} has changed in recent decades (high confidence).
    |</strong> In many areas since the 1990s, {Glossary.*Active_layer active layer} thicknesses increased by a few centimetres to tens of centimetres (medium confidence). In other areas, especially in northern North America, there were large interannual variations but few significant trends (high confidence). The thickness of the {Glossary.*Seasonally_frozen_ground seasonally frozen ground} in some non-{Glossary.*Permafrost permafrost} parts of the Eurasian continent likely decreased, in places by more than 30 cm from 1930 to 2000 (high confidence).
    |
